Here is the general workflow: either the new sale button is pressed opening the modal with no previous information -- this is to make a standalone sale without involving a workorder. inventory items are added by the user and the totals are tallied, then the checkout process commences. If the new sale button has not been pressed, that means the "checkout" button was pressed from the Items_WorkorderItems page. this button opens the checkout modal with the current open workorder in it, for the purposes of completing the workorder and sale.

** DO NOT USE A DEPOSIT SYSTEM (you will see a few deposit-related items in the current file, but that is a previous design)

when the modal opens with a workorder, we also must search for other open workorders the user has, so that we can combine them (user-selectable to if and how many they want to combine). list these clearly with the option to select/deselect them to add to the sale. 

We must be able to:
- take partial payment on a workorder (sometimes a customer pre-pays a certain portion of a workorder, so we must be able to record a partial payment on the workorder itself)
- split payments across cash and as many cards as necessary
- combine workorders as outlined above, while also splitting payment across them using cash and card transactions
- be network-failure proof --> this means the split transactions need to be stored in the db as completed in real time, in case we have to come back to the sale

also, when a workorder has been opened in the checkout modal, we must also allow the user to search for and add inventory items (by scanning in a upc or typing a search term) to the current sale. on-screen, we want the added items to be differentiated visually from the workorder ticket. however when the sale transaction is complete, the added items will be added to the workorder, as if they were added on in the main workorder edit screen process.

add a selection for if the user is paying by check (but this selection is conditional on the acceptChecks boolean in the settings db node).

take into account the useCardFee boolean in the settings object. add this to the sale if true, and use the percentage in cardFeePercent in settings.

use salesTaxPercent in settings for sales tax calculations.

REFUND DISCUSSION
For refunds, the user will open up the checkout modal by scanning a ticket in from the main page. you can choose if you want to separate refunds from sales, and if so may create a different modal screen that opens up when scanning in a sale id. include the word "sale" in the sale id so that the app knows that a sale is being scanned (instead of a workorder). 

for refunds, we will allow the user to either: 1) select items from the workorder that they want to refund 2) create a custom refund amount up to and including the total original sale, accounting for any previous refunds already completed. the user cannot start a refund for more than the total original sale under any circumstances. we must account for edge cases such as a previous custom refund, then the user comes back and wants to return an item, but that item exceeds the amount avaialable to refund. implement any other edge cases as you see fit.

use cardFeeRefund in settings to know whether to refund the card fee percentage to the customer or not.

